    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix complex multiplication bugs in FFT implementation affecting bfly3 accuracy\n\n### Summary\nThe ARM NEON and x86 SIMD implementations of complex multiplication functions contained critical bugs that caused incorrect results in FFT operations, particularly affecting the bfly3 radix-3 butterfly function. The issue was identified when users reported unexpected output from bfly3() calls.\n\nThe root cause was that several complex multiplication functions (cmult, cmac, and their 256-bit variants) were using non-conjugated values when computing the imaginary components of complex products. This led to mathematically incorrect FFT computations.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts.c`: Fixed x86 cmult function to use conjugated value for imaginary part computation\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts.c`: Fixed x86 cmac function to use conjugated value for imaginary part computation  \n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts.c`: Fixed ARM cmult function to compute bflip from bconj instead of original b\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts.c`: Fixed ARM cmac function to compute bflip from bconj instead of original b\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts.c`: Applied similar fixes to 256-bit variants (cmult_256, cmac_256)\n\n### Reproduction\nUsers reported that when calling bfly3() with specific input values, the output did not match expected mathematical results for radix-3 FFT operations. Under heavy FFT processing loads, this manifested as signal quality degradation in both DL and UL processing chains. The issue was more pronounced on ARM platforms due to the incorrect NEON implementation.\n\n"
}